Note:
Runtime cyclic-barrier API — the public rendezvous object for the Runa runtime
concurrency system.

A cyclic (reusable) barrier holds back a fixed number of cooperating threads
(the "parties") until all of them have arrived, then releases them all at once
and immediately resets itself for the next round. Unlike the mutex and condvar
wrappers in this directory, sync_core exposes NO barrier primitive: there is no
underlying OS barrier handle to delegate to. This module therefore BUILDS a real
barrier out of the two lower-level primitives sync_core does provide — a mutex
and a condition variable — implementing the arrival count, the trip logic, and
the generation counter itself.

RuntimeBarrier layout (48 bytes):
    offset 0:  mutex      — sync_core mutex handle guarding all barrier state
    offset 8:  condvar    — sync_core condvar handle threads block on
    offset 16: parties    — N, the number of threads each cycle waits for
    offset 24: count      — threads that have arrived in the CURRENT generation
    offset 32: generation — monotonically increasing cycle id

THE REUSE RACE AND ITS DEFENSE:
The classic broken barrier waits on a predicate like "count == 0" after the
trip. That races: the last thread resets count to 0 and broadcasts, but a
released waiter can re-enter barrier_wait for the NEXT round and increment count
before an earlier-released waiter has even woken from its condvar_wait. The slow
waiter then re-tests its predicate, still sees a small count, and blocks again —
permanently stranded one generation behind. The fix is a generation counter:
each waiting thread records the generation it arrived in (my_gen) and blocks
while generation is still equal to my_gen. The trip advances generation exactly
once, so every waiter from that cycle observes the change and leaves, while any
thread that has already moved on to the next cycle is operating on a strictly
greater generation and is unaffected by the stale count it might briefly see.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: RuntimeBarrier object layout
Constant RT_BARRIER_SIZE as Integer is 48
Constant RT_BARRIER_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant RT_BARRIER_OFF_CONDVAR as Integer is 8
Constant RT_BARRIER_OFF_PARTIES as Integer is 16
Constant RT_BARRIER_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 24
Constant RT_BARRIER_OFF_GENERATION as Integer is 32

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime barrier API
Constant BARRIER_OK as Integer is 0
Constant BARRIER_LEADER as Integer is 1
Constant BARRIER_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant BARRIER_ERR_INVALID as Integer is 0 minus 2

Process called "barrier_new" takes parties as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a reusable barrier for exactly "parties" threads. The synchronizing
    machinery (a mutex and a condition variable) is supplied by sync_core; this
    layer owns the counting, the trip decision, and the generation bookkeeping
    that turn those two primitives into a correct cyclic barrier.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reject a non-positive party count (a barrier of zero or negative width has no
    meaning) by returning 0. Allocate the 48-byte object, then create the
    sync_core mutex and condvar. Each acquired resource is released on a later
    failure so no handle or allocation leaks on the error path. Initialize count
    and generation to 0: the first cycle is generation 0 with no arrivals yet.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one sync_core mutex_create and one condvar_create
    (each allocates its own control block and an OS primitive). Cold path: run
    once per barrier lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Any failure returns 0 (NULL) after fully unwinding partial construction;
    callers MUST check the result before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    If parties is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let b be proc allocate from Memory with RT_BARRIER_SIZE
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc mutex_create from Sync
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with b
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cv be proc condvar_create from Sync
    If cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mtx
        proc deallocate from Memory with b
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_MUTEX, mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_CONDVAR, cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_PARTIES, parties
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_GENERATION, 0
    Return b
End Process

Process called "barrier_wait" takes b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until all parties have arrived at this barrier, then
    release the whole cohort together and arm the barrier for its next use. The
    final arrival of each cycle is designated the leader so a caller can run a
    single-threaded "phase boundary" action (merge results, advance an epoch)
    without external coordination.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the mutex so all reads and writes to count and generation are atomic
    with respect to other parties. Snapshot the current generation into my_gen,
    then register this arrival by incrementing count.

    If count now equals parties, this thread is the last arrival and TRIPS the
    barrier: it advances generation (publishing the trip to every blocked waiter),
    clears count to 0 for the next cycle, broadcasts the condvar to wake all
    waiters, releases the mutex, and returns BARRIER_LEADER. Exactly one thread
    per cycle reaches this branch, so exactly one leader is named per round.

    Otherwise this thread is an early arrival and must wait. It loops on
    condvar_wait while generation is still equal to my_gen. The loop is mandatory:
    condition variables permit spurious wakeups, and re-testing the generation on
    every wake means a thread only proceeds once the barrier has genuinely
    tripped. Because the predicate is the generation — not the count — a waiter
    that wakes after later threads have already begun the next cycle still sees
    generation advanced past my_gen and exits correctly, which is precisely what
    defeats the cyclic-barrier reuse race. condvar_wait atomically releases and
    re-acquires the mutex, so the mutex is held again on loop exit and is released
    before returning BARRIER_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex lock/unlock per call. Early arrivals block in the OS via condvar
    until the trip; the leader performs one broadcast that wakes the cohort. No
    busy-waiting and no per-thread allocation on the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null barrier returns BARRIER_ERR_NULL without touching memory. On every
    non-null path the mutex is released before the Process returns, so no caller
    leaves this Process still holding the lock.
    @End Security_Scope

    If b is equal to 0:
        Return BARRIER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_CONDVAR
    Let lock_result be proc mutex_lock from Sync with mtx
    If lock_result is not equal to 1:
        Return BARRIER_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let my_gen be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_GENERATION
    Let parties be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_PARTIES

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_COUNT
    Let new_count be count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_COUNT, new_count

    If new_count is equal to parties:
        Let next_gen be my_gen plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_GENERATION, next_gen
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_COUNT, 0
        proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with cv
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return BARRIER_LEADER
    Otherwise:
        Let current_gen be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_GENERATION
        While current_gen is equal to my_gen:
            proc condvar_wait from Sync with cv, mtx
            Set current_gen to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_GENERATION
        End While
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mtx
        Return BARRIER_OK
    End If
End Process

Process called "barrier_parties" takes b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report the fixed width of the barrier — the number of parties each cycle waits
    for. Useful for diagnostics and for callers that size worker pools to match.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the parties field. The value is immutable after construction, so this
    read needs no lock.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null barrier returns 0. Pure read; no state is modified.
    @End Security_Scope

    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_PARTIES
End Process

Process called "barrier_destroy" takes b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tear down a barrier that is no longer in use, releasing the underlying
    sync_core mutex and condvar and the runtime object itself.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Destroy the sync_core condvar and mutex (each frees its facade control block
    and the OS primitive), then deallocate the RuntimeBarrier. Must only be called
    once no thread is blocked in or about to enter barrier_wait.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One condvar_destroy plus one mutex_destroy plus one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null barrier returns BARRIER_ERR_NULL. Destroying a barrier with waiters
    still parked on it is a caller logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If b is equal to 0:
        Return BARRIER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_CONDVAR
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with b, RT_BARRIER_OFF_MUTEX
    proc condvar_destroy from Sync with cv
    proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mtx
    proc deallocate from Memory with b
    Return BARRIER_OK
End Process
